18
00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:22.000
Awesome. No worries. So first of all, my name's Hillary Pritchard. I'm born and bred in New Zealand. I go back about 13 generations. Our family come from orchards or farming as such.

19
00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:48.000
And environmental has been in our life for a long time. I'm 46 as it is. I've been fishing since I was a little kid. And you can clearly see that our oceans are struggling. I am dumbfounded after the video cameras of deep sea trawling have been released that a country so beautiful as ours and the rules and the regulations that we use in our country are even contemplating letting that into our sea waters.

20
00:06:49.000 --> 00:07:02.000
I think deep sea trawling just destroys everything and anything in that environment. And I don't think it's fair to us or to our next future generations that we allow businesses to come in and do that.

21
00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:09.000
I think a lot in this bill is wrong. And I think none of it is there to protect the oceans or to protect us as New Zealanders.

22
00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:24.000
I don't think allowing fishing companies or commercial fishing companies to be able to pull over to the next year or roll over their fish so that they can catch more of the limit or downsizing the fish is the solution out of this problem.

23
00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:34.000
I think we need to have a look into our oceans more and understand what is going on, how we can do this more sustainable so we can bring in fishing into New Zealand.

24
00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:42.000
It does make a lot of money. It is an extremely fun thing and all of us as humans and New Zealanders should be entitled to be able to do that.

25
00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:54.000
I think one of the other things that I'd like to bring up is that for the long-term effect of trawling we don't actually know what's going to happen.

26
00:07:54.000 --> 00:08:00.000
So I think to allow something like that and just hope that we can correct it in the long-term is just silly.

27
00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:07.000
I am a big believer of doing a no-fish for quite a few years, but I also understand that's unrealistic.

28
00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:21.000
But our oceans are very important and the bottom of the ocean with the sea corals and the environments and the ecosystems is definitely something that we need to protect.

29
00:08:21.000 --> 00:08:26.000
I'm happy with a couple of questions and then I'm quite happy to say my best.

30
00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:29.000
Oh no, if you've still got more to say you go for it.

31
00:08:29.000 --> 00:08:32.000
I have a whole lot more poise.

32
00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:38.000
I think we all understand as well that we've seen deep sea trawling around the world.

33
00:08:38.000 --> 00:08:42.000
We've seen the effect that it can have. The byproducts for instance with sailfish.

34
00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:52.000
Once we increase those all of a sudden we had more being increased to the bio to the bycatchers, which I think as well is a massive problem.

35
00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:59.000
I don't think game fish should be anywhere near commercial fishing or allowed.

36
00:08:59.000 --> 00:09:11.000
And for any New Zealander who's seen any footage of the cameras that is on those trawling nets, I would be shocked that anybody would think that it's a great idea to do in our waters.

37
00:09:11.000 --> 00:09:19.000
I think it's money that we could invest into the fishing company.

38
00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:22.000
We need information that we need to know.

39
00:09:22.000 --> 00:09:29.000
And I think as well that we could amend, like just demolish the bull until we do figure out what is going on in our oceans.

40
00:09:29.000 --> 00:09:40.000
I think a fair part of being New Zealand is being able to just catch a fishing rod and go out and catch a few fish for your kai moana and bring it home.

41
00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:48.000
Reducing the legal size limit of fish in an area to me suggests that that area is possibly outfished.

42
00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:57.000
I don't know how it would make sense to just start fishing smaller ones as I think taking away the babies or the breeders is obviously going to deplete.

43
00:09:57.000 --> 00:10:00.000
There's fish in that area.

44
00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:05.000
I think that's a very scary thing to have in our waters.

45
00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:11.000
I also believe that our oceans themselves being so close to Antarctica and where we are.

46
00:10:11.000 --> 00:10:13.000
I know that we are polluted.

47
00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:16.000
I know that we have all the problems that the rest of the world does as well.

48
00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:24.000
As New Zealanders, I'm kind of hoping that we all do the right thing and realise that we should be protecting our oceans in any form that we can.

49
00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:33.000
And fish, corals, everything that's even at the bottom of the ocean, the microorganisms, the ecosystems, it's all as important as it is out here.

50
00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:37.000
We do enough on our lands with protecting ecosystems.

51
00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:40.000
I think we need to start doing it now in our oceans.

52
00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:53.000
When you can follow people like Matt Watson who really do make a change in New Zealand and make you question what the laws and the rules and what should be going on and you look at somebody who's lived off seafood for a long time and moved to a beautiful place in Northland.

53
00:10:53.000 --> 00:10:58.000
For him to be fine and everybody else to be fine.

54
00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:03.000
You can't catch any crayfish for the next five years so the population can come back.

55
00:11:03.000 --> 00:11:08.000
That's amazing that we can do that as people and as humans.

56
00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:19.000
So let's keep those trawlers out, get them out of our country, change this bill, listen to all the New Zealanders and realise that this is not a smart idea for New Zealand.

57
00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:24.000
Fantastic. Thank you so much for your time, Hilary, and for your submission. We really appreciate it.

58
